[6] Argentina (Oran, Salta province)
Date: Wed 12 Oct 2011
Source: El Tribuno [in Spanish transl., summ. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.eltribuno.info/salta/83801-Confirman-que-la-nina-de-Oran-sufre-hantavirus.note.aspx


The director of epidemiology in the province, Alberto Gentile, stated
yesterday [11 Oct 2011] that a 7 year old girl had been admitted to
the Vicente de Paul Hospital in Oran on Friday [7 Oct 2011] with a
febrile picture that appeared to be [a] hantavirus [infection].
Preliminary tests by the Tropical Medicine Research Laboratory led to
a suspicion of a dengue [clinical] picture.

After confirmation [of a hantavirus infection], it was supposed
[learnt? - Mod.SH] that the girl and her family lives a house near
sugar cane plantations, "a place where there usually are rodent
species that are reservoirs of hanta[viruses]," mentioned the
epidemiologist.

In the 9 months of this year [2011], the number of confirmed
hantavirus cases in the province totals 17. During 2010, there were 30
and in 2009 there were 29.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The hantavirus most likely involved in this case is Oran virus.
However, without laboratory confirmation, it is not possible to say
with certainty which hantavirus was involved. As noted in ProMED-mail
archive number 20110430.1348, several hantaviruses have been
associated with human infection in Argentina: Andes virus (western
Argentina, in the long-tailed pygmy rice rat host, _Oligoryzomys
longicaudatus_); related Andes-like viruses Hu39694 (in central
Argentina; rodent host unknown); Lechiguana (in central Argentina in
the yellow pygmy rice rat _O. flavescens_); Oran (in north western
Argentina in _O. longicaudatus_); and Bermejo (western Argentina in
_O. flavescens_) virus.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of Oran
can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1mk5. - Mod.TY]

******
[7] Bolivia
Date: Thu 13 Oct 2010
Source: Bolivia [in Spanish, transl., summ.Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.bolivia.com/noticias/AutoNoticias/DetalleNoticia46029.asp


During 2011, hantavirus[es] have caused the deaths of 4 people who got
this rare but extremely serious disease, caused by a family of viruses
that are transmitted to humans when they breathe air contaminated with
urine, excrement, or saliva of rodents, according to a statement from
the local unit with national responsibility for influenza and
hantaviruses of the Ministry of Health, Adolfo Zarate.

According to reports from the Ministry of Health, they have 101
recorded suspicious [hantavirus infection] cases, 19 of which are
confirmed by departmental laboratories in Santa Cruz, Cochabamba,
Tarija, and Beni departments [state or province equivalents].

"As a ministry, we are taking measures necessary to avoid an increase
in cases. We are equipped with informative material and materials to
control rodents in the areas were there are these vectors [reservoirs]
that transmit the disease," explained Zarate.

The commonest symptoms of the disease are muscle pain, headache,
coughing, vomiting, diarrhea, and abdominal pain. Zarate stated that
the primary symptom of the disease is respiratory difficulty caused by
the accumulation of fluids in the lungs, a situation that can lead to
respiratory arrest. Currently, there is no specific treatment for
hantavirus [pulmonary] disease. Early intensive hospital care is the
only known measure.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The specific locations of these cases is not given in this report,
other than the departments where the laboratories have made the
diagnosis and presumably where these cases occurred. The specific
hantaviruses involved in these cases is not mentioned either.

The possible hantaviruses (and their rodent hosts, from a list kindly
provided by Dr Jim Mills, and their images) that might be involved in
these HPS cases are:

- Laguna Negra virus (_Calomys laucha_
http://www.cricyt.edu.ar/institutos/iadiza/ojeda/Akomolinaes.jpg and

_C. callosus_
http://www.faunaparaguay.com/Calomys%20callosus%20www.pybio.org%201.jpg),
- Bermejo virus (_Oligoryzomys chacoensis_
http://www.faunaparaguay.com/images/Oligoryzomys%20chacoensis%20enciso%2015jul11.jpg),
- Oran (_O. longicaudatus_
http://www.bios.niu.edu/frayjorge/rod6.jpg).

A map showing the location of the departments (state or province
equivalents) in Bolivia can be accessed at
http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/bolivia_admin_2006.jpg. An
interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Bolivia can be accessed at
http://healthmap.org/r/1mkc. - Mod.TY]
